ast and Internet viewings). 17 channels have a 4-week share of \u2265 1.0%.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://www.barb.co.uk/viewing-data/weekly-viewing-summary-new/|title=Weekly viewing summary Feb 24 - Mar 1 2020|publisher=BARB}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Channels with a viewing share of \u2265 1.0%, Mar 1 2020<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n! Channel !! Owner !! Free/Pay !! Four week share (%) !! Average daily minutes (mins:secs)\n|-\n| BBC One\t|| BBC || {{free}} || 20.50\t|| 39:11\n|-\n| ITV or STV\t    || ITV plc or STV Group || {{free}} ||  17.86\t|| 34:09\n|-\n| BBC Two\t|| BBC || {{free}} ||  5.36\t|| 10:15\n|-\n| Channel 4\t|| Channel 4 Television Corp ||  {{free}} || 5.00\t|| 9:33\n|-\n| Channel 5\t|| Channel 5 Broadcasting (ViacomCBS) ||  {{free}} || 3.76\t|| 7:12\n|-\n| ITV2\t|| ITV plc ||  {{free}} || 2.25\t|| 4:18\n|-\n| ITV3\t|| ITV plc ||  {{free}} || 1.96\t|| 3:44\n|-\n| E4\t|| Channel 4 Television Corp ||  {{free}} || 1.37\t|| 2:37\n|-\n| ITV4\t|| ITV plc ||  {{free}} || 1.34\t|| 2:34\n|-\n| BBC News || BBC || {{free}} || 1.33 || 2:32\n|-\n| CBeebies\t|| BBC ||  {{free}} || 1.25\t|| 2:24\n|-\n| Drama\t|| UKTV Media (BBC) ||  {{free}} || 1.25\t|| 2:23\n|-\n| Film4\t|| Channel 4 Television Corp ||  {{free}} || 1.17\t|| 2:14\n|-\n| Sky Sports Main Event\t|| Sky UK (Comcast) ||  {{nonfree|Subscription}} || 1.11\t|| 2:07\n|-\n| More 4 || Channel 4 Television Corp || {{free}} || 1.05\t|| 2:00\n|-\n| Quest || Discovery Inc || {{free}} || 1.03\t|| 1:58\n|-\n| Dave || UKTV Media (BBC) || {{free}} || 1.02\t|| 1:56\n|}\n\n==== Most viewed broadcaster groups ====\n\nAs of March 1 2020, there are 10 broadcaster groups with a four week share of \u2265 1.0% (although BARB reports sub-groups of BBC and ViacomCBS individually, and it's unclear what the 'ITV' group refers to)\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Broadcaster groups with a viewing share of \u2265 1%, Mar 1 2020<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.barb.co.uk/viewing-data/weekly-viewing-summary-new/|title=Three-screen viewing share UK TV & broadband households by broadcaster group 24 Feb - 1 Mar|publisher=BARB}}</ref>\n! Channel owner !! Share of total viewing time (%)\n|-\n| BBC || 31.38 \n|-\n| 'ITV'  || 24.28\n|-\n| Channel 4 Television Corp || 9.10\n|-\n| Sky UK (Comcast) || 8.95\n|-\n| Channel 5 Broadcasting (ViacomCBS) || 6.03\n|-\n| Discovery || 4.39\n|-\n| UKTV Media (BBC) || 4.17\n|-\n| Columbia Pictures (Sony) || 1.71\n|-\n| CBS AMC Networks (ViacomCBS/AMC) || 1.53\n|-\n| Viacom International Media Networks (ViacomCBS) || 1.27\n|}\n\n=== British Broadcasting Corporation (BBC) ===\n{{main|BBC}}\n{{See also|Category:BBC television channels in the United Kingdom|UKTV|Category:UKTV channels}}\n\n[[File:BBC.svg|150px|right]]\nThe BBC is the world's oldest and largest broadcaster, and is the country's principal [[public broadcasting|public service broadcaster]]. The BBC is funded primarily by a [[television licence]] and from sales of its programming to overseas markets. It does not carry [[television advertising|advertising]]. The licence fee is levied on all households that watch or record TV as it's being broadcast<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvlicensing.co.uk/check-if-you-need-one/|title=Official TV Licensing website \u2013 Do you need a TV Licence?}}</ref> and the fee is determined by periodic negotiation between the government and the BBC.\n\nIts first analogue terrestrial channel, the BBC Television Service, launched in 1936. It rebranded to BBC 1 in 1964, the same year that BBC 2 launched, the UK's third analogue terrestrial channel after ITV. Both channels styled as [[BBC One]] and [[BBC Two]] from 1997. BBC News 24 launched as an analogue cable channel in 1997, later rebranding to BBC News.  BBC Parliament, which was originally an analogue cable channel known as The Parliamentary Channel, was acquired by the BBC in 1998.  From 1998 onwards the BBC started digital TV transmissions, launching new channels and broadcasting via satellite in addition to terrestrial and cable. BBC Three closed as a broadcast channel in 2016, continuing as an Internet video service.\n\nThe BBC's Internet-based service iPlayer contains content from the BBC's TV channels, the Welsh-language public-service broadcaster S4C, as well as videos created from BBC radio programmes, with Radio 1 in particular appearing as a channel alongside the normal TV channels.\n\n[[UKTV]] is a commercial broadcaster owned by [[BBC Studios]], one of the BBC's commercial units.  Originating in 1992 with [[Gold_(UK_TV_channel)|UK Gold]], UKTV expanded its channels from 1997 onwards, with the BBC taking full ownership in June 2019. Unlike the BBC's public service channels, the UKTV channels contain advertising.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! !! Public service channels !! Commercial channels\n|-\n| {{free|Free channels}} || BBC One, BBC Two, BBC Four, BBC News, BBC Parliament, CBBC, CBeebies, BBC Scotland, BBC Alba, BBC Red Button ||  [[Dave (TV channel)|Dave]], [[Drama (British TV channel)|Drama]], [[Yesterday (TV channel)|Yesterday]]\n|-\n| {{nonfree|Subscription channels}} || None ||  [[Alibi (TV channel)|Alibi]], [[Eden (TV channel)|Eden]], [[Gold (UK TV channel)|Gold]], [[W (UK TV channel)|W]]\n|-\n| Internet TV services || BBC Three, BBC iPlayer || UKTV Play\n|}\n\n=== ITV ===\n{{main|ITV (TV channel)}}\n{{See also|Category:ITV franchisees|ITV plc|List of ITV channels}}\n\nITV is the network of fifteen regional commercial television franchises, founded in 1955 to provide competition to the [[BBC]]. ITV was the country's first [[commercial television]] provider funded by [[television commercials|advertisements]], and has been the most popular commercial channel through most of its existence. Through a series of mergers, takeovers and relaxation of regulation, thirteen of these companies are now owned by [[ITV plc]]; the other two are owned by [[STV Group (Scotland)|STV Group]]. ITV plc, the operator of all English, Welsh, [[Scotland|Southern Scotland]] and [[Channel Island]] franchises, had branded the channel as [[ITV (TV channel)|ITV1]] since 2001, with regional names being used prior to regional programmes only since 2002. The ITV name was restored in 2013. ITV plc also operate the [[Northern Ireland]] franchise under the [[UTV (TV channel)|UTV]] brand name. [[STV Group (Scotland)|STV Group]], which operates the two other Scottish franchises, has now unified the regions under the single name of [[STV (TV channel)|STV]]. ITV has been officially known as '''Channel 3''' since 1990, although this is seldom used to identify itself.\n\nITV plc also operates digital channels [[ITV2]], [[ITV3]], [[ITV4]], [[ITVBe]] and [[CITV]], some with HDTV streams. [[ITN]], a subsidiary, currently holds the national news franchise, and [[ITV Breakfast]] operates the breakfast franchise.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! !! ITV plc !! STV Group\n|-\n| {{free|Free channels}}  || ITV, ITV2, ITV3, ITV4, ITVBe, CITV || STV\n|-\n| {{nonfree|Subscription}} || ITV2 HD, ITV3 HD, ITV4 HD || None\n|-\n| Internet TV Services || ITV Hub || STV Player\n|}\n\n=== Channel 4 ===\n{{main|Channel 4}}\n{{see also|Channel Four Television Corporation}}\n[[File:Channel 4 logo 2015.svg|right|frameless|128x128px]]\nLaunched in 1982, Channel 4 is a state-owned national broadcaster which is funded by its commercial activities (including advertising). Channel 4 has expanded greatly after gaining greater independence from the [[Independent Broadcasting Authority|IBA]], especially in the multi-channel digital world launching [[E4 (TV channel)|E4]], [[Film4]], [[More4]], [[4Music]], [[4seven]] and various [[timeshift channel|timeshift services]]. Since 2005, it has been a member of the [[Freeview (UK)|Freeview]] consortium, and operates one of the six digital terrestrial multiplexes with [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] as [[Digital 3&4]]. Since the advent of digital television, Channel 4 is now also broadcast in [[Wales]] across all digital platforms. Channel 4 was the first British channel not to carry regional variations for programming, however it does have 6 set advertising regions.\n\nWith Bauer Media Group, Channel 4 jointly owns a range of music channels under the Box Plus Network banner.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! !! Channel 4 channels !! Box Plus Network\n|-\n| {{free|Free channels}}  || Channel 4, Channel 4 HD, More4, Film4, E4, 4seven, 4seven HD || The Box, Box Hits, 4Music, Kiss, Magic, Kerrang!\n|-\n| {{nonfree|Subscription}} || More4 HD, Film4 HD, E4 HD || None\n|-\n| Internet TV Services || All 4 || Box Plus Network\n|}\n\n=== Sky ===\n{{main|Sky UK}}\n{{See also|Category:Sky television channels}}\n[[File:SKY Basic Logo.svg|128x128px|right]]\nSky is a European broadcaster owned by global American media conglomerate [[Comcast]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thestreet.com/investing/comcast-tops-q3-earnings-forecast-after-40-billion-sky-deal-14756907|title=Comcast Tops Q3 Earnings Forecast After $40 Billion Sky Deal|last=Baccardax|first=Martin|date=2018-10-25|work=TheStreet|access-date=2018-11-08|language=en-US}}</ref>   Sky Television launched in 1989, with a 4-channel service received via satellite.  The channels at launch were [[Sky One|Sky Channel]], [[Sky News]], [[Sky Cinema|Sky Movies]] and [[Eurosport]]. They were initially free to receive, and Sky Movies was the first to move to a subscription early in 1990. Sky News was the UK's first dedicated news channel. The new service was the UK's first consumer satellite TV service, beating rival [[British_Satellite_Broadcasting|BSB]], with which Sky would later merge to become BSkyB.  Sky's satellite service grew to become a subscription platform through which Sky offer their own channels, pay-per-view services and channels from other broadcasters. Sky's digital platform launched in 1998, with the original analogue service closing in 2001. Sky was acquired by Comcast in 2018.\n\nSince 2012, Sky operate [[Now TV (Sky)|NOW TV]], an Internet TV streaming service offering subscriptions without a fixed-term contract.\n\nSky's channel portfolio has grown greatly since the launch of digital TV.  Sky make their channels available via rival cable and Internet services as well as their own satellite service and NOW TV.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! !! Sky UK !! At The Races !! [[NBCUniversal]]\n|-\n|  {{free|Free channels}}  || [[Challenge (TV channel)|Challenge]], [[Pick (TV channel)|Pick]], [[Sky News]] || None || CNBC\n|-\n| {{nonfree|Subscription}} || [[Sky One]], [[Sky Two]], [[Sky Arts]], [[Sky Atlantic]], [[Sky Comedy]], [[Sky Crime]], [[Sky Witness (TV channel)|Sky Witness]] <br>[[Sky Cinema]] channels: Action, Comedy, Disney, Drama, Family, Greats, Hits, Premiere, Sci-fi & Horror, Select, Thriller <br>[[Sky Sports]] channels: Action, Arena, Cricket, Extra, F1, Football, Golf, Main Event, Mix, Premier League, Sports News||  [[Sky Sports Racing]] || E!, Syfy\n|-\n| {{nonfree|Pay-per-view}} || Sky Sports Box Office || None || None\n|-\n| Internet TV Services || Sky Go, NOW TV || ATR Player || Hayu\n|}\n\n=== ViacomCBS ===\n{{Main|ViacomCBS}}\n{{See also|Channel 5 (UK)}}\n\n[[File:Channel 5 (UK) 2016.svg|128x128px|right]]\nChannel 5 was the fifth analogue terrestrial channel to launch, in March 1997. Due to constraints with the available UHF frequencies at the time, many households had to retune their [[videocassette recorder|video recorders]], which shared the frequency on their RF output with the frequency used by Channel 5's new broadcasts. Channel 5 was the first terrestrial channel to also broadcast via satellite. From 2006 onwards, Channel 5 launched new digital channels and an Internet on-demand service. After changing ownership several times, in May 2014 Channel 5 and its sister channels were acquired by Viacom, an American [[media conglomerate]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-27240335 |title=Viacom to buy Channel 5 for \u00a3450m |publisher=BBC News |date=1 May 2014 |accessdate=13 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nBy the time it acquired Channel 5, Viacom already operated a large number of subscription channels in the UK, including the MTV, Nickelodeon and Comedy Central channels, which are available via Sky TV, Virgin Media and NOW TV.  In terms of viewing share, the combined viewing across ViacomCBS's channels make the group the UK's 5th largest broadcaster, according to BARB's viewing figures for March 1 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.barb.co.uk/viewing-data/weekly-viewing-summary-new/ |title=Weekly viewing summary by broadcaster group|publisher=BARB |date=1 March 2020 |accessdate=29 March 2020|quote=8.83%}}</ref> Viacom merged with CBS in December 2019.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! !! Channel 5 Broadcasting !! Viacom International Media Networks !!  CBS AMC Networks UK (co-owned)\n|-\n| {{free|Free channels}}  || Channel 5, 5Star, 5USA, Paramount Network, 5Select || None || CBS Drama, CBS Justice, CBS Reality\n|-\n| {{nonfree|Subscription}} || None || MTV, MTV Music, MTV Base, MTV Hits, MTV OMG, Club MTV, MTV Rocks, MTV Classic, Nickelodeon, Nicktoons, Nick Jr., NickJr 2, Comedy Central, Comedy Central Extra, BET || None\n|-\n| Internet TV Services || My5 || None || None\n|}\n\n== Local television ==\n{{further|Local television in the United Kingdom}}\nOn 18 January 2011, then [[Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport]] [[Jeremy Hunt (politician)|Jeremy Hunt]] announced his intentions to set up a network of local television channels across the UK. The initial plan was to create a network of local television channels, connected through a national backbone. This plan would create a television network similar to that of the [[network affiliate|network-affiliate]] model in the United States and Canada.<ref>{{cite news|title=Jeremy Hunt outlines plans for 'local TV' \u2013 BBC News|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-12220187|accessdate=19 January 2011|publisher=BBC News}}</ref> In June 2011, however, it was announced that the national spine plan would be scrapped, and a 'bottom-up' approach would be followed instead, where channels are individually licensed.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sweney|first1=Mark|title=Jeremy Hunt confirms major shift in local TV policy|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2011/jun/02/jeremy-hunt-local-tv|accessdate=2 June 2011|work=The Guardian|date=2 June 2011}}</ref>\n\nRichard Horwood, a former [[Trinity Mirror]] executive, announced that when the local television channels are first licensed, he intends to create a television network called Channel 6; this will be a network of local television channels, with Channel 6 supplying the prime time schedule (similar to the American network-affiliate model).<ref>{{cite news|last1=Conlan|first1=Tara|title=Has Richard Horwood found a way to make local TV profitable?|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2010/nov/18/richard-horwood-local-tv|accessdate=18 November 2010|work=The Guardian|date=18 November 2010}}</ref> Another operator, which has announced its intentions to set up a network of local television channels with a television network connecting them, is City TV Broadcasting. That company says it is basing its operations on the [[Citytv]] television system in Canada, but there does not appear to be any official affiliation with the latter's owner, [[Rogers Communications]]. City TV is initially bidding on a channel to be based in Birmingham.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.citytvbroadcasting.co.uk/about-city-tv-broadcasting/|title=About City TV Broadcasting|author=City TV Broadcasting|accessdate=17 December 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120731092626/http://www.citytvbroadcasting.co.uk/about-city-tv-broadcasting/|archivedate=31 July 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n== Programming ==\n\nBritish television differs from other countries, such as the [[Television in the United States|United States]], in as much that programmes produced in the United Kingdom do not generally have a long season run of around 20 weeks. Instead, they are produced in a series, a set of episodes varying in length, usually aired over a period of a few months. See [[List of British television series]].\n\n=== 100 Greatest British Television Programmes ===\n{{main|100 Greatest British Television Programmes}}\n\n'''100 Greatest British Television Programmes''' was a list compiled in 2000 by the [[British Film Institute]] (BFI), chosen by a poll of industry professionals, to determine what were the greatest British television programmes of any genre ever to have been screened. Although not including any programmes made in 2000 or later, the list is useful as an indication of what were generally regarded as the most successful British programmes of the 20th century. The top 10 programmes are:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Rank !! Programme !! Channel !! Year\n|-\n|1 || ''[[Fawlty Towers]]'' || '''BBC2''' || 1975\u20131979\n|-\n|2 || ''[[Cathy Come Home]]'' (''[[The Wednesday Play]]'') || '''BBC1''' || 1966\n|-\n|3 || ''[[Doctor Who]]'' || '''BBC1''' || 1963\u20131989, 1996, 2005\u2013present\n|-\n|4 || ''[[The Naked Civil Servant (film)|The Naked Civil Servant]]'' || '''ITV''' || 1975\n|-\n|5 || ''[[Monty Python's Flying Circus]]'' || '''BBC2''' || 1969\u20131974\n|-\n|6 || ''[[Blue Peter]]'' || '''BBC1''' || 1958\u2013present\n|-\n|7 || ''[[Boys from the Blackstuff]]'' || '''BBC2''' || 1982\n|-\n|8 || ''[[Parkinson (TV series)|Parkinson]]'' || '''BBC1/ITV''' || 1971\u20131982, 1998\u20132007\n|-\n|9 || ''[[Yes Minister]]'' / ''Yes, Prime Minister'' || '''BBC2''' || 1980\u20131988\n|-\n|10 || ''[[Brideshead Revisited (TV serial)|Brideshead Revisited]]'' || '''ITV''' || 1981\n|-\n|}\n\n=== 100 Greatest TV Moments ===\n\n'''100 Greatest TV Moments''' was a list compiled by Channel 4 in 1999. The top 10 entries are:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Rank !! Programme !! Channel !! Year !! Moment\n|-\n| 1 || News || BBC1 / BBC2 / ITV || 1969 || The [[Apollo 11]] moon landing\n|-\n| 2 || News || BBC1 / BBC2 / ITV || 1990 || The [[Nelson Mandela#Release|release of Nelson Mandela]]\n|-\n| 3 || News || BBC1 / BBC2 / ITV || 1997 || [[Portillo moment|Michael Portillo loses his seat]] in the [[1997 United Kingdom general election|general election]], which came to symbolise the end of the period of [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] government which had begun in 1979 with [[Margaret Thatcher]] as [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]]\n|-\n| 4 || News || BBC1 / BBC2 / ITV || 1997 || The [[death of Diana, Princess of Wales]]\n|-\n| 5 || News || BBC1 / BBC2 / ITV || 1989 || [[Berlin Wall#The fall, 1989|The fall of the Berlin Wall]]\n|-\n| 6 || [[1966 FIFA World Cup]] || BBC1 / ITV || 1966 || [[1966 FIFA World Cup Final|Final]]: England beats Germany 4\u20132; commentator [[Kenneth Wolstenholme]]'s quotation \"[[They think it's all over]]\"\n|-\n| 7 || ''[[Only Fools and Horses]]'' || BBC1 || 1989 || \"[[Yuppy Love]]\": [[Del Boy]] falls through a bar flap\n|-\n| 8 || [[Live Aid]] || BBC1 || 1985 || The multi-venue rock concert to raise funds for the [[1984\u20131985 famine in Ethiopia|famine]] of [[Ethiopia]]\n|-\n| 9 || ''[[Blackadder Goes Forth]]'' || BBC1 || 1989 || \"[[Goodbyeee]]\": the protagonists go [[Going over the top|over the top]]\n|-\n| 10 || News || BBC / ITV || 1963 || [[John F. Kennedy assassination]]\n|}\n\n=== List of most watched television broadcasts ===\n{{main|List of most watched television broadcasts in the United Kingdom}}\nThe majority of special events attracting large audiences are often carried on more than one channel. The most-watched programme of all time on a single channel is the 1973 wedding ceremony of [[The Princess Anne]], shown only on BBC1. The figures in these tables represent the average viewership achieved by each broadcast during its run-time and do not include peak viewership.\n\n* Post-1981 figures verified by the [[Broadcasters' Audience Research Board]] (BARB)\n* Pre-1981 figures supplied by the [[British Film Institute]] (BFI)\n{| c