5", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1337x"}
{"title_page": "Zinnia elegans", "text_new": "{{speciesbox\n|image = Zinnienbl\u00fcte Zinnia elegans stack15 20190722-RM-7222254.jpg\n|genus = Zinnia\n|species = elegans\n|authority = [[Jacq.]] 1793, conserved name not Jacq. 1797 nor Sess\u00e9 & Moc. 1890\n|synonyms_ref = <ref>[http://www.tropicos.org/Name/2701599 Tropicos, ''Zinnia elegans'' Jacq.]</ref><ref>[http://www.theplantlist.org/tpl1.1/record/gcc-91964 The Plant List, ''Zinnia violacea'' Cav.]</ref>\n|synonyms =\n* ''Zinnia violacea'' <small>Cav.</small>\n* ''Crassina elegans'' <small>(Jacq.) Kuntze</small>\n* ''Zinnia australis'' <small>F.M.Bailey</small>\n}}\n\n'''''Zinnia elegans''''', known as '''youth-and-age''',<ref name=BSBI07>{{cite web |title=BSBI List 2007 |publisher=Botanical Society of Britain and Ireland |url=http://www.bsbi.org.uk/BSBIList2007.xls |format=xls |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6VqJ46atN?url=http://www.bsbi.org.uk/BSBIList2007.xls |archive-date=2015-01-25 |accessdate=2014-10-17 |url-status=dead }}</ref> '''common zinnia''' or '''elegant zinnia''', an [[annual plant|annual]] [[flowering plant]] of the genus ''[[Zinnia]]'', is one of the best known zinnias. It is native to Mexico but grown as an ornamental in many places and naturalised in several places including scattered locations in South and Central America, the West Indies, the United States, Australia, and Italy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bonap.net/MapGallery/County/Zinnia%20elegans.png|title=Biota of North America Program 2014 county distribution map|website=bonap.net}}</ref><ref>[http://luirig.altervista.org/flora/taxa/index1.php?scientific-name=zinnia+elegans Altervista Flora Italiana, ''Zinnia elegans'' Jacq.]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://bie.ala.org.au/species/Zinnia+elegans|title=Zinnia elegans  : Zinnia \u2013 Atlas of Living Australia|first=Atlas of Living|last=Australia|website=bie.ala.org.au}}</ref><ref>Berendsohn, W.G. & A.E. Araniva de Gonz\u00e1lez. 1989. Listado b\u00e1sico de la Flora Salvadorensis: Dicotyledonae, Sympetalae (pro parte): Labiatae, Bignoniaceae, Acanthaceae, Pedaliaceae, Martyniaceae, Gesneriaceae, Compositae. Cuscatlania 1(3): 290\u20131\u2013290\u201313</ref><ref>Dodson, C.H., A.H. Gentry & F.M. Valverde Badillo. 1985. La Flora de Jauneche: Los R\u00edos, Ecuador 1\u2013512. Banco Central del Ecuador, Quito</ref><ref>Balick, M. J., M. H. Nee & D.E. Atha. 2000. Checklist of the vascular plants of Belize. Memoirs of The New York Botanical Garden 85: i\u2013ix, 1\u2013246</ref>\n\n== Description ==\nThe uncultivated plant grows to about 30 in (76&nbsp;cm) in height. It has solitary flower heads about 2 inches (5&nbsp;cm) across. The purple ray  florets surround black and yellow discs. The [[lanceolate]] leaves are opposite the flower heads.\n\n== History ==\nThe species was first collected in 1789 at [[Tixtla]], [[Guerrero]], by [[Mart\u00edn Sess\u00e9 y Lacasta|Sess\u00e9]] and [[Jos\u00e9 Mariano Moci\u00f1o|Moci\u00f1o]]. It was formally described as ''Zinnia violacea'' by [[Antonio Jos\u00e9 Cavanilles|Cavanilles]] in 1791. [[Nikolaus Joseph von Jacquin|Jacquin]] described it again in 1792 as ''Zinnia elegans'', which was the name that Sess\u00e9 and Mo\u00e7i\u00f1o had used in their manuscript of ''Plantae Novae Hispaniae'', which was not published until 1890.<ref>Kirkbride, J. H. & J. H. Wiersma. (2007). Proposal to conserve the name ''Zinnia elegans'' against ''Z. violacea''. ''Taxon'' 56(3):958-959.</ref> The genus was named by [[Carl von Linn\u00e9]] after the German botanist [[Johann Gottfried Zinn]], who described the species now known as ''[[Zinnia peruviana]]'' in 1757 as ''Rudbeckia foliis oppositis hirsutis ovato-acutis, calyce imbricatus, radii petalis pistillatis''. Linn\u00e9 realised that it was not a ''[[Rudbeckia]]''.\n\n== Habits ==\nFlowering occurs between spring to fall.\n\n== Cultivation ==\nThe garden zinnia was bred via [[Hybrid (biology)|hybridisation]] from the wild form. Zinnias are popular garden plants with hundreds of [[cultivars]] in many flower colours, sizes and forms. There are giant forms with flower heads up to 6 in (15&nbsp;cm) in diameter.\n\nFlower colours range from white and cream to pinks, reds, and purples, to green, yellow, [[apricot (colour)|apricot]], orange, [[salmon (colour)|salmon]], and bronze. Some are striped, speckled or bicoloured. There are \"[[pom-pom]]\" forms that resemble [[dahlias]]. Sizes range from dwarf varieties of less than 6 inches (15&nbsp;cm) in height to 3 feet (90&nbsp;cm) tall. The [[powdery mildew]] common to zinnias in humid climates is less common in recently developed varieties, which are resistant.\n\nOther cultivars include 'Magellan', 'Envy Double', 'Fireworks', 'Purple Prince', 'Blue Point Purple', 'Profusion Cherry', 'Profusion Orange', 'Star Gold', 'Star Orange', and several white-flowered types such as 'Crystal White', 'Purity', and 'Profusion White'. Mixed-colour seed selections are available.\n\n=== Growth ===\nZinnias grow easily and prefer well-drained, [[loam]]y soil and full sun. They grow best in dry, warm, frost-free regions, and many kinds are drought-tolerant. Some may be grown indoors.\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Zinnia July 2010-1.jpg|''Zinnia elegans'' with a wasp\nFile:Zinnia elegans at Kadavoor.jpg|''Zinnia elegans'' in [[Kerala]]\nFile:Abejorro (Bombus lucorum) en una Zinnia elegans, Jard\u00edn Bot\u00e1nico, M\u00fanich, Alemania, 2013-09-08, DD 01.JPG|Bumblebee (''Bombus lucorum'') on a ''Zinnia elegans'', Botanic Garden of Munich, Germany\nFile:Plumchen 002.jpg|Closeup of flower center, ''Z. Elegans''\nFile:Zinnia elegans flowers (Rajbiraj, Saptari, Nepal) 2015-04-25.jpg| ''Zinnia elegans'' flower Nepal\n</gallery>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Sources ==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Wikispecies|Zinnia}}\n\n* [http://www.floridata.com/ref/z/zinn_ele.cfm Floridata: ''Zinnia elegans'']\n* [http://www.plantoftheweek.org/week433.shtml Plant of the week: ''Zinnia elegans'']\n* [http://www.gardenguides.com/112-zinnia-garden-basics-flower-annual-zinnia-elegans.html Garden Guides: ''Zinnia elegans'']\n* [http://www.wildflowerinformation.org/Wildflower.asp?ID=25 Wildflower Information: ''Zinnia elegans'']\n* [http://www.ces.ncsu.edu/depts/hort/consumer/factsheets/annuals/zinnia_elegans.html North Carolina State University: ''Zinnia elegans'']\n* [http://www.flowersofindia.net/catalog/slides/Zinnia.html Flowers of India: ''Zinnia elegans'']\n* [http://www.theplantlist.org/tpl/search?q=Zinnia+elegans Kew Plant List]\n* [http://www.ipni.org/ipni/simplePlantNameSearch.do?find_wholeName=Zinnia+elegans  The International Plant Names Index]\n\n\n{{Taxonbar|from1=Q15245321|from2=Q205087}}\n\n[[Category:Zinnia|elegans]]\n[[Category:Flora of Mexico]]\n[[Category:Butterfly food plants]]\n", "text_old": "{{speciesbox\n|image = Zinnienbl\u00fcte Zinnia elegans stack15 20190722-RM-7222254.jpg\n|genus = Zinnia\n|species = elegans\n|authority = [[Jacq.]] 1793, conserved name not Jacq. 1797 nor Sess\u00e9 & Moc. 1890\n|synonyms_ref = <ref>[http://www.tropicos.org/Name/2701599 Tropicos, ''Zinnia elegans'' Jacq.]</ref><ref>[http://www.theplantlist.org/tpl1.1/record/gcc-91964 The Plant List, ''Zinnia violacea'' Cav.]</ref>\n|synonyms =\n* ''Zinnia violacea'' <small>Cav.</small>\n* ''Crassina elegans'' <small>(Jacq.) Kuntze</small>\n* ''Zinnia australis'' <small>F.M.Bailey</small>\n}}\n\n'''''Zinnia elegans''''', known as '''youth-and-age''',<ref name=BSBI07>{{cite web |title=BSBI List 2007 |publisher=Botanical Society of Britain and Ireland |url=http://www.bsbi.org.uk/BSBIList2007.xls |format=xls |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6VqJ46atN?url=http://www.bsbi.org.uk/BSBIList2007.xls |archive-date=2015-01-25 |accessdate=2014-10-17 |url-status=dead }}</ref> '''common zinnia''' or '''elegant zinnia''', an [[annual plant|annual]] [[flowering plant]] of the genus ''[[Zinnia]]'', is one of the best known zinnias. It is native to Mexico but grown as an ornamental in many places and naturalised in several places including scattered locations in South and Central America, the West Indies, the United States, Australia, and Italy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bonap.net/MapGallery/County/Zinnia%20elegans.png|title=Biota of North America Program 2014 county distribution map|website=bonap.net}}</ref><ref>[http://luirig.altervista.org/flora/taxa/index1.php?scientific-name=zinnia+elegans Altervista Flora Italiana, ''Zinnia elegans'' Jacq.]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://bie.ala.org.au/species/Zinnia+elegans|title=Zinnia elegans  : Zinnia \u2013 Atlas of Living Australia|first=Atlas of Living|last=Australia|website=bie.ala.org.au}}</ref><ref>Berendsohn, W.G. & A.E. Araniva de Gonz\u00e1lez. 1989. Listado b\u00e1sico de la Flora Salvadorensis: Dicotyledonae, Sympetalae (pro parte): Labiatae, Bignoniaceae, Acanthaceae, Pedaliaceae, Martyniaceae, Gesneriaceae, Compositae. Cuscatlania 1(3): 290\u20131\u2013290\u201313</ref><ref>Dodson, C.H., A.H. Gentry & F.M. Valverde Badillo. 1985. La Flora de Jauneche: Los R\u00edos, Ecuador 1\u2013512. Banco Central del Ecuador, Quito</ref><ref>Balick, M. J., M. H. Nee & D.E. Atha. 2000. Checklist of the vascular plants of Belize. Memoirs of The New York Botanical Garden 85: i\u2013ix, 1\u2013246</ref>\n\n== Description ==\nThe uncultivated plant grows to about 30 in (76&nbsp;cm) in height. It has solitary flower heads about 2 inches (5&nbsp;cm) across. The purple ray  florets surround black and yellow discs. The [[lanceolate]] leaves are opposite the flower heads.\n\n== History ==\nThe species was first collected in 1789 at [[Tixtla]], [[Guerrero]], by [[Mart\u00edn Sess\u00e9 y Lacasta|Sess\u00e9]] and [[Jos\u00e9 Mariano Moci\u00f1o|Moci\u00f1o]]. It was formally described as ''Zinnia violacea'' by [[Antonio Jos\u00e9 Cavanilles|Cavanilles]] in 1791. [[Nikolaus Joseph von Jacquin|Jacquin]] described it again in 1792 as ''Zinnia elegans'', which was the name that Sess\u00e9 and Mo\u00e7i\u00f1o had used in their manuscript of ''Plantae Novae Hispaniae'', which was not published until 1890.<ref>Kirkbride, J. H. & J. H. Wiersma. (2007). Proposal to conserve the name ''Zinnia elegans'' against ''Z. violacea''. ''Taxon'' 56(3):958-959.</ref> The genus was named by [[Carl von Linn\u00e9]] after the German botanist [[Johann Gottfried Zinn]], who described the species now known as ''[[Zinnia peruviana]]'' in 1757 as ''Rudbeckia foliis oppositis hirsutis ovato-acutis, calyce imbricatus, radii petalis pistillatis''. Linn\u00e9 realised that it was not a ''[[Rudbeckia]]''.\n\n== Habits ==\nFlowering occurs between spring to fall.\n\n== Cultivation ==\nThe garden zinnia was bred via [[Hybrid (biology)|hybridisation]] from the wild form. Zinnias are popular garden plants with hundreds of [[cultivars]] in many flower colours, sizes and forms. There are giant forms with flower heads up to 6 in (15&nbsp;cm) in diameter.\n\nFlower colours range from white and cream to pinks, reds, and purples, to green, yellow, [[apricot (colour)|apricot]], orange, [[salmon (colour)|salmon]], and bronze. Some are striped, speckled or bicoloured. There are \"[[pom-pom]]\" forms that resemble [[dahlias]]. Sizes range from dwarf varieties of less than 6 inches (15&nbsp;cm) in height to 3 feet (90&nbsp;cm) tall. The [[powdery mildew]] common to zinnias in humid climates is less common in recently developed varieties, which are resistant.\n\nOther cultivars include 'Magellan', 'Envy Double', 'Fireworks', 'Purple Prince', 'Blue Point Purple', 'Profusion Cherry', 'Profusion Orange', 'Star Gold', 'Star Orange', and several white-flowered types such as 'Crystal White', 'Purity', and 'Profusion White'. Mixed-colour seed selections are available.\n\n=== Growth ===\nZinnias grow easily and prefer well-drained, [[loam]]y soil and full sun. They grow best in dry, warm, frost-free regions, and many kinds are drought-tolerant. Some may be grown indoors.\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Zinnia July 2010-1.jpg|''Zinnia elegans'' with a wasp\nFile:Zinnia elegans at Kadavoor.jpg|''Zinnia elegans'' in [[Kerala]]\nFile:Abejorro (Bombus lucorum) en una Zinnia elegans, Jard\u00edn Bot\u00e1nico, M\u00fanich, Alemania, 2013-09-08, DD 01.JPG|Bumblebee (''Bombus lucorum'') on a ''Zinnia elegans'', Botanic Garden of Munich, Germany\nFile:Plumchen 002.jpg|Closeup of flower center, ''Z. Elegans''\n</gallery>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Sources ==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Wikispecies|Zinnia}}\n\n* [http://www.floridata.com/ref/z/zinn_ele.cfm Floridata: ''Zinnia elegans'']\n* [http://www.plantoftheweek.org/week433.shtml Plant of the week: ''Zinnia elegans'']\n* [http://www.gardenguides.com/112-zinnia-garden-basics-flower-annual-zinnia-elegans.html Garden Guides: ''Zinnia elegans'']\n* [http://www.wildflowerinformation.org/Wildflower.asp?ID=25 Wildflower Information: ''Zinnia elegans'']\n* [http://www.ces.ncsu.edu/depts/hort/consumer/factsheets/annuals/zinnia_elegans.html North Carolina State University: ''Zinnia elegans'']\n* [http://www.flowersofindia.net/catalog/slides/Zinnia.html Flowers of India: ''Zinnia elegans'']\n* [http://www.theplantlist.org/tpl/search?q=Zinnia+elegans Kew Plant List]\n* [http://www.ipni.org/ipni/simplePlantNameSearch.do?find_wholeName=Zinnia+elegans  The International Plant Names Index]\n\n\n{{Taxonbar|from1=Q15245321|from2=Q205087}}\n\n[[Category:Zinnia|elegans]]\n[[Category:Flora of Mexico]]\n[[Category:Butterfly food plants]]\n", "name_user": "Bijay chaurasia", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eGallery", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zinnia_elegans"}
{"title_page": "Valerie Taylor (diver)", "text_new": "{{Undisclosed paid|date=February 2020}}\n'''Valerie May Taylor''' (born 9 November 1935)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.today/dbRkU|title=Talking Heads - Ron and Valerie Taylor|date=2012-12-31|website=archive.ph|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref> is a global marine pioneer,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/local/stories/2015/08/19/4296443.htm|title=Pioneering underwater filmmaker Valerie Taylor: making friends with sharks|last=Corporation|first=Australian Broadcasting|date=2015-08-19|website=Conversations with Richard Fidler|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref> conservationist, multi-awarded [[photographer]] and [[Filmmaking|filmmaker]] <ref name=\":0\"/> and an inaugural member of the [[International Scuba Diving Hall of Fame|diving hall-of-fame]].<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.australiangeographic.com.au/environmentalists-conservationists-and-scientists/valerie-taylor-oam/|title=Valerie Taylor OAM|website=Australian Geographic|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref> Through her media profile she has communicated to mass audiences the wonders, behaviours and joys of the natural world, especially the marine environment. She has long implored governments, business and the public of the importance of the [[Conservation movement|conservation]] of our oceans and their inhabitants.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-08-28/marine-campaigner-valerie-taylor-urges-mps-to-block-marine-park/5703972|title=Conservationist protests SA marine park changes|date=2014-08-28|website=ABC News|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref>{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix   = AM\n| name               = Valerie May Taylor\n| image              = Valerie Taylor.JPG\n| birth_name         = Valerie May Heighes\n| birth_date         = 9 November 1935\n| birth_place        = Sydney, NSW Australia\n| nationality        = Australian\n| occupation         = Professional Diver, Underwater Photographer and Cinematographer, Author/Illustrator\n| spouse             = Ron Taylor (1963-2012)\n}}\n\n== Early life ==\nBorn in Paddington, Sydney on 9 November 1935, Taylor spent her early years in [[Sydney]]. Her mother was a housewife and her father an engineer for [[Exide|Exide Batteries]]. The family moved to New Zealand in 1939 to set up a battery factory there, but were unable to return to Australia when WWII broke out.<ref name=\":1\"/> At 12 years of age Taylor contracted [[polio]] during the [[1948 polio epidemic]]. Isolated from her family, friends and schooling she slowly recovered with the support of the \u2018[[Sister Kenny]] Treatment and Rehabilitation Method\u2019. Taylor fell behind in her studies and left school at 15 years of age to work for the NZ Film Unit drawing for an animation studio. She was already showing her talents as an artist.<ref name=\":1\"/>\n\nTaylor turned to Sydney with her family to settle in the beach side suburb of [[Port Hacking]] where she took up spearfishing to provide food for the family. Spearfishing opened her eyes to the underwater world. She became an Australian champion spearfisher and met her future husband, [[Ron Taylor]], at the St George's Spearfishing Club.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/11700946/The-most-glamorous-shark-hunter-in-the-world.html|title=The most glamorous shark hunter in the world|last=Hart|first=Anna|date=2015-06-28|access-date=2019-11-15|issn=0307-1235}}</ref><ref name=\"docs.google.com\">{{Cite web|url=https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1V_aoM5e4uBnGjGJgWzmbGQ7Cy5Z-40aWlNXoq7cJGkc/pub?single=true&gid=0&output=html|title=AUF Spearfishing Championship Trophies|website=docs.google.com|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nAlthough starting their aquatic careers as competitive spearfishers,<ref name=\"docs.google.com\"/> Valerie and Ron's respect for the underwater world grew. They downed their spears in favour of cameras and began successful careers making marine documentaries. The Taylors' introduced Australia and the world to the wonders of marine life and particularly sharks.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.sea.museum/en/2012/09/12/ron-and-valerie-taylor-and-their-quest-to-protect|title=Ron and Valerie Taylor and their quest to protect|website=Australian National Maritime Museum|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref>\n\nThe list of credits and awards for Valerie Taylor is extensive.<ref name=\":3\"/> She and Ron were the first people to film Great White sharks [[1992 cageless shark-diving expedition|without the protection of a cage]]. They made countless shark films including [[Blue Water White Death|Blue Water, White Death]] where they swam cageless among a school of Oceanic White Tip sharks feeding on a whale carcass.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pressreader.com/australia/the-australian-womens-weekly/20170201/281706909394764|title=PressReader.com - Your favorite newspapers and magazines.|website=www.pressreader.com|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref> The documentary was a cinema hit and caught the attention of American film director [[Steven Spielberg]]. They were called on to shoot the real Great White Shark sequences for [[Jaws (film)|Jaws]]. In addition to the 1000s of hours of film and television and their various published works, Valerie's conservation work in Australia and around the world is notable.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/subscribe/news/1/?sourceCode=TAWEB_WRE170_a_GGL&dest=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/arts/review/steven-spielbergs-jaws-recalled-by-valerie-taylor-as-film-turns-40/news-story/31813a7526aaf76e488dce59d535c30a&memtype=anonymous&mode=premium&v21suffix=12-b&nk=4841d0835ff95c71e5e77506e9300a5f-1573829102|title=Subscribe to The Australian {{!}} Newspaper home delivery, website, iPad, iPhone & Android apps|website=www.theaustralian.com.au|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref>\n\nIn 1967 a Belgian scientific expedition asked the Taylors' to join their endeavour to record life on the [[Great Barrier Reef]]. Over several months, Valerie dove the entire length of the Great Barrier Reef from [[Lady Elliot Island]] up to the Torres Strait - a feat perhaps unsurpassed even today.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Taylor|first=Valerie|last2=Borschmann|first2=Gregg|date=1996|title=Valerie Taylor interviewed by Gregg Borschmann in the Environmental awareness in Australia oral history project|url=https://catalogue.nla.gov.au/Record/1138790|journal=Environmental awareness in Australia oral history project}}</ref> Over the decades, Valerie's conservation efforts included campaigning to prevent oil exploration in [[Ningaloo Marine Park (Commonwealth waters)|Ningaloo Marine Park]], overturning mining rights on Coral Sea Islands, winning protection for many places on the Great Barrier Reef before it was given [[World Heritage]] status, and lobbying for marine sanctuary zones in South Australia.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/environment/conservation/shark-expert-honoured-for-conservation-20100614-y9ve.html|title=Shark expert honoured for conservation|date=2010-06-14|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adelaidenow.com.au/news/south-australia/shark-expert-valerie-taylor-visits-sa-to-campaign-against-changes-to-marine-parks-laws/news-story/6a0472b546f7cfc531c0c233997dcffb|title=Shark expert Taylor in one-woman marine park protest|date=2014-08-28|website=www.adelaidenow.com.au|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref>\n\nIn 1986, Valerie was appointed by his Royal Highness [[Prince Bernhard of Lippe-Biesterfeld|Prince Bernhard]] of the Netherlands, the \u2018Rider of the Order of the Golden Ark\u2019 for marine conservation. She was recognised for her successful efforts protecting of the habitat of the \u2018[[Potato grouper|potato cod]]\u2019 near Lizard Island - the first gazetted protection of the Great Barrier Reef.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=http://collections.anmm.gov.au/en/objects/164737/papua-new-guinean-shark-propeller-used-by-ron-and-valerie-ta;jsessionid=DBD5C784D87D46330002A04440D9CBE1|title=Papua New Guinean shark propeller used by Ron and Valerie Taylor|website=collections.anmm.gov.au|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref>\n\nAt 66 years old she was still actively promoting conservation and diving with sharks and was awarded the [[Centenary Medal]] for service to Australian society in marine conservation and the Australian Senior Achiever of the Year.<ref name=\":9\"/> In 2008 Valerie received the [[Australian Geographic]] Lifetime of Conservation award.<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.australiangeographic.com.au/podcast/valerie-taylor-shark-lady-and-dead-set-aussie-legend/|title=Valerie Taylor - Shark lady and dead set Aussie legend|website=Australian Geographic|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010 Valerie was awarded an [[Order of Australia|AM]] For service to conservation and the environment as an advocate for the protection and preservation of marine wildlife and habitats, particularly the Great Barrier Reef and Ningaloo Reef, and as an underwater cinematographer and photographer.<ref name=\":9\"/>\n\nValerie also excelled as an underwater photographer and her underwater images graced the pages of the [[National Geographic|National Geographic Magazine]] including some pioneering macro images of coral and invertebrates on the Great Barrier Reef that made front cover in 1973.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kararosenlund.com/2018/10/valerie-taylor-behind-the-scenes/|title=Kara Rosenlund - Valerie Taylor \u2013 Behind the Scenes|website=Kara Rosenlund|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref> This compelling front page image also caught the attention of [[Lars-Eric Lindblad]], and Valerie and Ron spent a decade traveling the world on the little red and white ship called the Lindblad Explorer lecturing to travellers on board.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.expeditions.com/why-us/expedition-team/staff-bio/valerie-taylor/|title=Expedition Team, Travel Tour Guide - Lindblad Expeditions|website=www.expeditions.com|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref>\n\nDuring the early 1980s Valerie began experiments with sharks wearing a steel mesh suit. Her experiments were ground-breaking, world firsts that contributed to a new understanding of the relative bite power of various shark species. The 1981 front cover of National Geographic magazine featured Valerie, off the coast of California, during one of these experiments with Blue sharks wearing this chainmail suit.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://divingalmanac.com/first-shark-observation-suit/|title=First shark observation suit|website=Diving Almanac & Book of Records|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref>\n\nIn 1981 Valerie was awarded the [[NOGI Awards|NOGI award]] for Arts, Academy of Underwater Arts & Sciences, presented by the Academy of Underwater Arts and Sciences (AUAS) to diving luminaries.<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite web|url=http://collections.anmm.gov.au/objects/203563/photograph-depicting-valerie-taylor-holding-a-fish;jsessionid=2AC5606B43D3FFAA8AD95DB94D3AB217|title=Photograph depicting Valerie Taylor holding a fish|website=collections.anmm.gov.au|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref>\n\nHer photographic talents saw her awarded the 1997 American Nature Photographer of the year award (sponsored by the American Press Club) for a picture of a whale shark swimming with her nephew in Ningaloo Marine Park.<ref name=\"TAYLOR, Valerie\">{{Cite web|url=https://divingalmanac.com/taylor-valerie/|title=TAYLOR, Valerie|website=Diving Almanac & Book of Records|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref> By 2000 she was inducted into the Women Divers Hall of Fame.<ref name=\"TAYLOR, Valerie\"/>\n\n[https://www.abc.net.au/news/2012-09-09/acclaimed-shark-expert-ron-taylor-dies/4251372 Valerie\u2019s husband Ron passed] away from [[Leukemia]] in 2012<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2012/sep/10/jaws-shark-cameraman-ron-taylor-dies|title=Jaws shark cameraman Ron Taylor dies|last=Press|first=Associated|date=2012-09-10|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-11-15|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> but Valerie has continued her unflinching focus on marine conservation and communication. She has illustrated and written a children's book,<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Undersea-Artistry-Valerie-Taylor-Illustrations/dp/197757114X|website=www.amazon.com|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref> campaigned against ocean plastic pollution overfishing and published her memoirs .<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.hachette.com.au/ben-mckelvey-valerie-taylor/valerie-taylor-an-adventurous-life-the-remarkable-story-of-the-trailblazing-ocean-conservationist-photographer-and-shark-expert|title=Valerie Taylor: An Adventurous Life: The remarkable story of the trailblazing ocean conservationist, photographer and shark expert by Ben Mckelvey - Books|website=www.hachette.com.au|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref>\n\nMrs Valerie Taylor AM has dedicated more than 50 years of her life bringing the wonders of the natural world into our living rooms through her keen observations and storytelling ability. She has fearlessly lobbied for a better understanding and management of our marine life and their habitats. She has inspired people the world over to immerse themselves in the marine world and its conservation. Without the benefit of a secondary school or tertiary education she has become a role model for generations of scientists.\n\n== Endeavours ==\n\n=== Documentaries ===\n\n**''Playing with Sharks'' for [[Movietone News]], 1962<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/books/the-average-person-would-have-died-in-the-first-week-shark-expert-valerie-taylor-20180308-p4z3dx.html|title='The average person would have died in the first week': shark expert Valerie Taylor|last=Dapin|first=Mark|date=2018-03-09|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref>\n** ''Shark Hunters'', 1963; with [[Ben Cropp]]<ref name=\":1\" />\n** ''Slaughter at Saumarez'', 1964<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thejohnharding.wordpress.com/2009/10/20/21/|title=RON TAYLOR\u2019S \u201cSlaughter at Saumarez\u201d (1964) 360P|last=HARDING|first=Author JOHN H.|date=2009-10-19|website=John Harding|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref>\n** ''Skindiving Paradise'', 1965<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sharksavers.org/en/blogs-news/community-voice/a-tribute-to-ron-taylor/|title=Shark Savers :: A tribute to Ron Taylor|website=www.sharksavers.org|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref>\n** ''Revenge of a Shark Victim'', 1965; about [[Rodney Fox]] (re-edited by [[Robert Raymond]] into ''SHARK'' which subsequently received a [[Logie Award]])<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm0853294/|title=Valerie Taylor|website=IMDb|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref>\n** ''Surf Scene'', 1965<ref name=\":2\" />\n** ''Will the Barrier Reef Cure Claude Clough?'', 1966<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nfsa.gov.au/collection/curated/will-great-barrier-reef-cure-claude-clough|title=Will The Great Barrier Reef Cure Claude Clough?|last=Australia|first=National Film and Sound Archive of|date=2019-11-16|website=www.nfsa.gov.au|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref>\n** ''Belgian Scientific Expedition'', for University of Li\u00e8ge 1967<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://coralseaoz.blogspot.com/2012/07/birds.html|title=The Coral Sea: No.10 'THE BELGIAN EXPEDITION to the GBR' (1967)|last=Harding|first=John H.|date=2012-07-07|website=The Coral Sea|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref>\n** ''The Underwater World of Ron Taylor'', 1967, narrated live by Ron Taylor<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cinematographer.org.au/cms/page.asp?ID=20179|title=Ron Taylor AM ACS & Valerie Taylor AM - Australian Cinematographers Society|website=www.cinematographer.org.au|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref>\n** ''The Cave Divers'', 1967; for [[W.D. & H.O. Wills|W.D. & H.O. Wills (Aust)]]<ref>{{Citation|title=The Cave Divers|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt9531006/|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref>\n** ''Sharks'', 1975; for [[Time-Life Television]]<ref name=\":0\"/>\n** ''The Great Barrier Reef'', 1978; for Time-Life Television<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ozmovies.com.au/movie/reef|title=The Reef - Review - Photos - Ozmovies|website=www.ozmovies.com.au|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref>\n** ''The Wreck of the Yongala'', 1981<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Viduka|first=Andrew|date=2011|title=Managing underwater cultural heritage: A case study of SS Yongala|url=http://search.informit.com.au/documentSummary;dn=137483878548865;res=IELAPA|journal=Historic Environment|volume=23|issue=2|pages=12}}</ref>\n** ''The Great Barrier Reef'' (IMAX), 1982; technical consultants<ref name=\":3\" />\n** ''Operation Shark Bite'', 1982<ref name=\":0\" />\n** ''Give Sharks a Chance'', 1991; with [[Richard Dennison]] for [[National Geographic Society]] and the [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]]<ref name=\":2\" />\n** ''Shark Shocker'' 1993 (with Richard Dennison) for [[Channel 4|Channel 4 UK]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oranafilms.com.au/shark-shocker/|title=Shark Shocker {{!}} Orana Films|website=www.oranafilms.com.au|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref>\n** ''Shadow over the Reef'', 1993<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.screenaustralia.gov.au/the-screen-guide/c/Ron-Taylor-Film-Productions/8423/,%20https://www.screenaustralia.gov.au/the-screen-guide/c/Ron-Taylor-Film-Productions/8423/|title=Ron Taylor Film Productions - The Screen Guide|website=Screen Australia|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref>\n** ''Mystique of the Pearl'', for [[Film Australia]], 1995<ref name=\":2\" />\n** ''Shark Pod'', 1996<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.screenaustralia.gov.au/the-screen-guide/t/shark-pod-1997/13291/|title=Shark POD (1997) - The Screen Guide - Screen Australia|website=www.screenaustralia.gov.au|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref>\n** ''Shadow of the Shark'', 1999; for [[Australian Geographic]]<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n=== Television ===\n\n* ''[[Skippy the Bush Kangaroo]]'', [[List of Skippy the Bush Kangaroo episodes#Season 1 (1968\u20131969)|Episode 3]] \u2013 ''Golden Reef'' (1968) \u2013 original story & [[List of Skippy the Bush Kangaroo episodes#Season 2 (1969)|Episode 57]] \u2013 ''The Shark Taggers''(1969) \u2013 underwater sequences<ref name=\":2\" />\n* ''Contrabandits'' (30 episode series), 1967\u201368; underwater sequences and diving instruction for cast<ref name=\":2\" />\n* ''[[Barrier Reef (TV series)|Barrier Reef]]'' (39-episode series), 1971\u20131972; direction of underwater photography, stunt work and minor acting roles<ref name=\":3\" />\n* ''Taylor's Inner Space'' (13-episode series), 1972\u20131973 with soundtrack composed by [[Sven Libaek]] and narration by [[William Shatner]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/filmosearch/?role=nm0508715|title=Most Popular Movies and TV Shows With Sven Libaek|website=IMDb|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref>\n* ''[[Those Amazing Animals]]'', 1980\u20131981; contributed to underwater segments<ref name=\":2\" />\n* ''[[Fortress (1986 film)|Fortress]]'', 1985; underwater sequences<ref name=\":2\" />\n* ''Blue Wilderness'' (6 episodes)[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1992_cageless_shark-diving_expedition], 1992; with Richard Dennison for National Geographic and the Australian Broadcasting Corporation<ref name=\":2\" />\n* ''[[Flipper (1995 TV series)|Flipper]]'', 1995 series; underwater still photography<ref>{{Citation|title=Flipper (1995 TV series)|date=2019-09-20|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Flipper_(1995_TV_series)&oldid=916791620|work=Wikipedia|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref>\n\n=== Films ===\n\n* ''[[Age of Consent (film)|Age of Consent]]'', 1968<ref name=\":2\" />\n* ''[[The Intruders (1969 film)|The Intruders]]'' (also known as ''Skippy and the Intruders''), 1969<ref>{{Citation|title=The Intruders|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0130795/|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref>\n* ''[[Blue Water White Death|Blue Water, White Death]]'', 1971<ref>{{Citation|title=Blue Water, White Death|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0146496/|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref>\n* ''[[Jaws (film)|Jaws]]'', 1975<ref name=\":2\" />\n* ''[[Orca (film)|Orca]]'', 1976; live shark sequences<ref name=\":2\" />\n* ''[[The Last Wave]]'', 1977; underwater sequences<ref>{{Citation|title=The Last Wave (1977) - IMDb|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0076299/fullcredits|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref>\n* ''[[Jaws 2]]'', 1978<ref name=\":2\" />\n* ''[[Gallipoli (1981 film)|Gallipoli]]'', 1981; underwater sequences<ref>{{Citation|title=Gallipoli|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0082432/|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref>\n* ''[[A Dangerous Summer]]'' , 1982: underwater sequences<ref>{{Citation|title=A Dangerous Summer|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0082233/|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref>\n* ''[[The Year of Living Dangerously (film)|Year of Living Dangerously]]'', 1982<ref>{{Citation|title=The Year of Living Dangerously|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0086617/|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref>\n* ''[[The Blue Lagoon (1980 film)|The Blue Lagoon]]'', 1980; underwater sequences<ref name=\":2\" />\n* ''The Silent One'', 1983<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sbs.com.au/movies/review/silent-one-review|title=The Silent One Review|website=SBS Movies|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref>\n* ''[[Sky Pirates]]'', 1984, underwater sequences<ref>{{Citation|title=Sky Pirates (1986) - IMDb|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0091964/fullcredits|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref>\n* ''[[Frog Dreaming]]'', 1986<ref>{{Citation|title=The Quest|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0091810/|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref>\n* ''[[The Rescue (1988 film)|The Rescue]]'', for Walt Disney, 1987\n* ''[[Return to the Blue Lagoon]]'', 1990, underwater sequences<ref name=\":2\" />\n* ''[[Honeymoon in Vegas]]'', 1991, underwater sequences<ref name=\":2\" />\n* ''[[Police Story 4: First Strike]]'', 1995; underwater sequences<ref name=\":2\" />\n* ''[[The Island of Dr. Moreau (1996 film)|The Island of Dr Moreau]]'', 1995, live shark sequences<ref>{{Citation|title=The Island of Dr. Moreau|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0116654/|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref>\n\n=== Books ===\n\n* ''The Undersea Artistry'', 2017, Illustrated<ref name=\":4\" />\n* ''An Adventurous Life'', 2019, Memoirs<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n== Awards and Achievements ==\n\n* 1981 \u2013 NOGI award for Arts, Academy of Underwater Arts & Sciences<ref name=\":11\" />\n* 1986 \u2013 [[Order of the Golden Ark]] presented by his Royal Highness, [[Prince Bernhard of the Netherlands]]<ref name=\":8\" />\n* 1993 \u2013 SSI Platinum Pro 5000 Diver<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.divessi.com/en-IC/inside-ssi/pro-recognition/|title=SSI PROFESSIONAL RECOGNITION|website=www.divessi.com|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref>\n* 1997: American Nature Photographer of the year award (sponsored by the American Press Club) for a picture of a [[whale shark]] swimming with her nephew in Ningaloo Marine Park<ref name=\":7\" />\n* 2000 \u2013 membership of the Women Divers Hall of Fame<ref name=\":9\"/>\n* 2001 \u2013 the Centenary Medal and the Australian Senior Achiever of the year<ref name=\":9\" />\n* 2010 \u2013 Member of the [[Order of Australia]] (AM)<ref name=\":10\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Australian photographers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Order of Australia]]\n[[Category:Australian filmmakers]]\n[[Category:1935 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{Undisclosed paid|date=February 2020}}\n'''Valerie May Taylor''' (born 9 November 1935)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.today/dbRkU|title=Talking Heads - Ron and Valerie Taylor|date=2012-12-31|website=archive.ph|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref> is a global marine pioneer,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/local/stories/2015/08/19/4296443.htm|title=Pioneering underwater filmmaker Valerie Taylor: making friends with sharks|last=Corporation|first=Australian Broadcasting|date=2015-08-19|website=Conversations with Richard Fidler|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref> conservationist, multi-awarded [[photographer]] and [[Filmmaking|filmmaker]] <ref name=\":0\"/> and an inaugural member of the [[International Scuba Diving Hall of Fame|diving hall-of-fame]].<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.australiangeographic.com.au/environmentalists-conservationists-and-scientists/valerie-taylor-oam/|title=Valerie Taylor OAM|website=Australian Geographic|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref> Through her media profile she has communicated to mass audiences the wonders, behaviours and joys of the natural world, especially the marine environment. She has long implored governments, business and the public of the importance of the [[Conservation movement|conservation]] of our oceans and their inhabitants.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-08-28/marine-campaigner-valerie-taylor-urges-mps-to-block-marine-park/5703972|title=Conservationist protests SA marine park changes|date=2014-08-28|website=ABC News|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref>{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix   = AM\n| name               = Valerie May Taylor\n| image              = Valerie Taylor.JPG\n| birth_name         = Valerie May Heighes\n| birth_date         = 9 November 1935\n| birth_place        = Sydney, NSW Australia\n| nationality        = Australian\n| occupation         = Professional Diver, Underwater Photographer and Cinematographer, Author/Illustrator\n| spouse             = Ron Taylor (1963-2012)\n}}\n\n== Early life ==\nBorn in Paddington, Sydney on 9 November 1935, Taylor spent her early years in [[Sydney]]. Her mother was a housewife and her father an engineer for [[Exide|Exide Batteries]]. The family moved to New Zealand in 1939 to set up a battery factory there, but were unable to return to Australia when WWII broke out.<ref name=\":1\"/> At 12 years of age Taylor contracted [[polio]] during the [[1948 polio epidemic]]. Isolated from her family, friends and schooling she slowly recovered with the support of the \u2018[[Sister Kenny]] Treatment and Rehabilitation Method\u2019. Taylor fell behind in her studies and left school at 15 years of age to work for the NZ Film Unit drawing for an animation studio. She was already showing her talents as an artist.<ref name=\":1\"/>\n\nTaylor turned to Sydney with her family to settle in the beach side suburb of [[Port Hacking]] where she took up spearfishing to provide food for the family. Spearfishing opened her eyes to the underwater world. She became an Australian champion spearfisher and met her future husband, [[RoRon Taylor]], at the St George's Spearfishing Club.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/11700946/The-most-glamorous-shark-hunter-in-the-world.html|title=The most glamorous shark hunter in the world|last=Hart|first=Anna|date=2015-06-28|access-date=2019-11-15|issn=0307-1235}}</ref><ref name=\"docs.google.com\">{{Cite web|url=https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1V_aoM5e4uBnGjGJgWzmbGQ7Cy5Z-40aWlNXoq7cJGkc/pub?single=true&gid=0&output=html|title=AUF Spearfishing Championship Trophies|website=docs.google.com|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nAlthough starting their aquatic careers as competitive spearfishers,<ref name=\"docs.google.com\"/> Valerie and Ron's respect for the underwater world grew. They downed their spears in favour of cameras and began successful careers making marine documentaries. The Taylors' introduced Australia and the world to the wonders of marine life and particularly sharks.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.sea.museum/en/2012/09/12/ron-and-valerie-taylor-and-their-quest-to-protect|title=Ron and Valerie Taylor and their quest to protect|website=Australian National Maritime Museum|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref>\n\nThe list of credits and awards for Valerie Taylor is extensive.<ref name=\":3\"/> She and Ron were the first people to film Great White sharks [[1992 cageless shark-diving expedition|without the protection of a cage]]. They made countless shark films including [[Blue Water White Death|Blue Water, White Death]] where they swam cageless among a school of Oceanic White Tip sharks feeding on a whale carcass.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pressreader.com/australia/the-australian-womens-weekly/20170201/281706909394764|title=PressReader.com - Your favorite newspapers and magazines.|website=www.pressreader.com|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref> The documentary was a cinema hit and caught the attention of American film director [[Steven Spielberg]]. They were called on to shoot the real Great White Shark sequences for [[Jaws (film)|Jaws]]. In addition to the 1000s of hours of film and television and their various published works, Valerie's conservation work in Australia and around the world is notable.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/subscribe/news/1/?sourceCode=TAWEB_WRE170_a_GGL&dest=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/arts/review/steven-spielbergs-jaws-recalled-by-valerie-taylor-as-film-turns-40/news-story/31813a7526aaf76e488dce59d535c30a&memtype=anonymous&mode=premium&v21suffix=12-b&nk=4841d0835ff95c71e5e77506e9300a5f-1573829102|title=Subscribe to The Australian {{!}} Newspaper home delivery, website, iPad, iPhone & Android apps|website=www.theaustralian.com.au|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref>\n\nIn 1967 a Belgian scientific expedition asked the Taylors' to join their endeavour to record life on the [[Great Barrier Reef]]. Over several months, Valerie dove the entire length of the Great Barrier Reef from [[Lady Elliot Island]] up to the Torres Strait - a feat perhaps unsurpassed even today.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Taylor|first=Valerie|last2=Borschmann|first2=Gregg|date=1996|title=Valerie Taylor interviewed by Gregg Borschmann in the Environmental awareness in Australia oral history project|url=https://catalogue.nla.gov.au/Record/1138790|journal=Environmental awareness in Australia oral history project}}</ref> Over the decades, Valerie's conservation efforts included campaigning to prevent oil exploration in [[Ningaloo Marine Park (Commonwealth waters)|Ningaloo Marine Park]], overturning mining rights on Coral Sea Islands, winning protection for many places on the Great Barrier Reef before it was given [[World Heritage]] status, and lobbying for marine sanctuary zones in South Australia.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/environment/conservation/shark-expert-honoured-for-conservation-20100614-y9ve.html|title=Shark expert honoured for conservation|date=2010-06-14|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adelaidenow.com.au/news/south-australia/shark-expert-valerie-taylor-visits-sa-to-campaign-against-changes-to-marine-parks-laws/news-story/6a0472b546f7cfc531c0c233997dcffb|title=Shark expert Taylor in one-woman marine park protest|date=2014-08-28|website=www.adelaidenow.com.au|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref>\n\nIn 1986, Valerie was appointed by his Royal Highness [[Prince Bernhard of Lippe-Biesterfeld|Prince Bernhard]] of the Netherlands, the \u2018Rider of the Order of the Golden Ark\u2019 for marine conservation. She was recognised for her successful efforts protecting of the habitat of the \u2018[[Potato grouper|potato cod]]\u2019 near Lizard Island - the first gazetted protection of the Great Barrier Reef.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=http://collections.anmm.gov.au/en/objects/164737/papua-new-guinean-shark-propeller-used-by-ron-and-valerie-ta;jsessionid=DBD5C784D87D46330002A04440D9CBE1|title=Papua New Guinean shark propeller used by Ron and Valerie Taylor|website=collections.anmm.gov.au|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref>\n\nAt 66 years old she was still actively promoting conservation and diving with sharks and was awarded the [[Centenary Medal]] for service to Australian society in marine conservation and the Australian Senior Achiever of the Year.<ref name=\":9\"/> In 2008 Valerie received the [[Australian Geographic]] Lifetime of Conservation award.<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.australiangeographic.com.au/podcast/valerie-taylor-shark-lady-and-dead-set-aussie-legend/|title=Valerie Taylor - Shark lady and dead set Aussie legend|website=Australian Geographic|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010 Valerie was awarded an [[Order of Australia|AM]] For service to conservation and the environment as an advocate for the protection and preservation of marine wildlife and habitats, particularly the Great Barrier Reef and Ningaloo Reef, and as an underwater cinematographer and photographer.<ref name=\":9\"/>\n\nValerie also excelled as an underwater photographer and her underwater images graced the pages of the [[National Geographic|National Geographic Magazine]] including some pioneering macro images of coral and invertebrates on the Great Barrier Reef that made front cover in 1973.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kararosenlund.com/2018/10/valerie-taylor-behind-the-scenes/|title=Kara Rosenlund - Valerie Taylor \u2013 Behind the Scenes|website=Kara Rosenlund|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref> This compelling front page image also caught the attention of [[Lars-Eric Lindblad]], and Valerie and Ron spent a decade traveling the world on the little red and white ship called the Lindblad Explorer lecturing to travellers on board.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.expeditions.com/why-us/expedition-team/staff-bio/valerie-taylor/|title=Expedition Team, Travel Tour Guide - Lindblad Expeditions|website=www.expeditions.com|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref>\n\nDuring the early 1980s Valerie began experiments with sharks wearing a steel mesh suit. Her experiments were ground-breaking, world firsts that contributed to a new understanding of the relative bite power of various shark species. The 1981 front cover of National Geographic magazine featured Valerie, off the coast of California, during one of these experiments with Blue sharks wearing this chainmail suit.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://divingalmanac.com/first-shark-observation-suit/|title=First shark observation suit|website=Diving Almanac & Book of Records|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref>\n\nIn 1981 Valerie was awarded the [[NOGI Awards|NOGI award]] for Arts, Academy of Underwater Arts & Sciences, presented by the Academy of Underwater Arts and Sciences (AUAS) to diving luminaries.<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite web|url=http://collections.anmm.gov.au/objects/203563/photograph-depicting-valerie-taylor-holding-a-fish;jsessionid=2AC5606B43D3FFAA8AD95DB94D3AB217|title=Photograph depicting Valerie Taylor holding a fish|website=collections.anmm.gov.au|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref>\n\nHer photographic talents saw her awarded the 1997 American Nature Photographer of the year award (sponsored by the American Press Club) for a picture of a whale shark swimming with her nephew in Ningaloo Marine Park.<ref name=\"TAYLOR, Valerie\">{{Cite web|url=https://divingalmanac.com/taylor-valerie/|title=TAYLOR, Valerie|website=Diving Almanac & Book of Records|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref> By 2000 she was inducted into the Women Divers Hall of Fame.<ref name=\"TAYLOR, Valerie\"/>\n\n[https://www.abc.net.au/news/2012-09-09/acclaimed-shark-expert-ron-taylor-dies/4251372 Valerie\u2019s husband Ron passed] away from [[Leukemia]] in 2012<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2012/sep/10/jaws-shark-cameraman-ron-taylor-dies|title=Jaws shark cameraman Ron Taylor dies|last=Press|first=Associated|date=2012-09-10|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-11-15|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> but Valerie has continued her unflinching focus on marine conservation and communication. She has illustrated and written a children's book,<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Undersea-Artistry-Valerie-Taylor-Illustrations/dp/197757114X|website=www.amazon.com|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref> campaigned against ocean plastic pollution overfishing and published her memoirs .<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.hachette.com.au/ben-mckelvey-valerie-taylor/valerie-taylor-an-adventurous-life-the-remarkable-story-of-the-trailblazing-ocean-conservationist-photographer-and-shark-expert|title=Valerie Taylor: An Adventurous Life: The remarkable story of the trailblazing ocean conservationist, photographer and shark expert by Ben Mckelvey - Books|website=www.hachette.com.au|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref>\n\nMrs Valerie Taylor AM has dedicated more than 50 years of her life bringing the wonders of the natural world into our living rooms through her keen observations and storytelling ability. She has fearlessly lobbied for a better understanding and management of our marine life and their habitats. She has inspired people the world over to immerse themselves in the marine world and its conservation. Without the benefit of a secondary school or tertiary education she has become a role model for generations of scientists.\n\n== Endeavours ==\n\n=== Documentaries ===\n\n**''Playing with Sharks'' for [[Movietone News]], 1962<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/books/the-average-person-would-have-died-in-the-first-week-shark-expert-valerie-taylor-20180308-p4z3dx.html|title='The average person would have died in the first week': shark expert Valerie Taylor|last=Dapin|first=Mark|date=2018-03-09|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref>\n** ''Shark Hunters'', 1963; with [[Ben Cropp]]<ref name=\":1\" />\n** ''Slaughter at Saumarez'', 1964<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thejohnharding.wordpress.com/2009/10/20/21/|title=RON TAYLOR\u2019S \u201cSlaughter at Saumarez\u201d (1964) 360P|last=HARDING|first=Author JOHN H.|date=2009-10-19|website=John Harding|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref>\n** ''Skindiving Paradise'', 1965<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sharksavers.org/en/blogs-news/community-voice/a-tribute-to-ron-taylor/|title=Shark Savers :: A tribute to Ron Taylor|website=www.sharksavers.org|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref>\n** ''Revenge of a Shark Victim'', 1965; about [[Rodney Fox]] (re-edited by [[Robert Raymond]] into ''SHARK'' which subsequently received a [[Logie Award]])<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm0853294/|title=Valerie Taylor|website=IMDb|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref>\n** ''Surf Scene'', 1965<ref name=\":2\" />\n** ''Will the Barrier Reef Cure Claude Clough?'', 1966<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nfsa.gov.au/collection/curated/will-great-barrier-reef-cure-claude-clough|title=Will The Great Barrier Reef Cure Claude Clough?|last=Australia|first=National Film and Sound Archive of|date=2019-11-16|website=www.nfsa.gov.au|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref>\n** ''Belgian Scientific Expedition'', for University of Li\u00e8ge 1967<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://coralseaoz.blogspot.com/2012/07/birds.html|title=The Coral Sea: No.10 'THE BELGIAN EXPEDITION to the GBR' (1967)|last=Harding|first=John H.|date=2012-07-07|website=The Coral Sea|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref>\n** ''The Underwater World of Ron Taylor'', 1967, narrated live by Ron Taylor<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cinematographer.org.au/cms/page.asp?ID=20179|title=Ron Taylor AM ACS & Valerie Taylor AM - Australian Cinematographers Society|website=www.cinematographer.org.au|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref>\n** ''The Cave Divers'', 1967; for [[W.D. & H.O. Wills|W.D. & H.O. Wills (Aust)]]<ref>{{Citation|title=The Cave Divers|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt9531006/|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref>\n** ''Sharks'', 1975; for [[Time-Life Television]]<ref name=\":0\"/>\n** ''The Great Barrier Reef'', 1978; for Time-Life Television<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ozmovies.com.au/movie/reef|title=The Reef - Review - Photos - Ozmovies|website=www.ozmovies.com.au|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref>\n** ''The Wreck of the Yongala'', 1981<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Viduka|first=Andrew|date=2011|title=Managing underwater cultural heritage: A case study of SS Yongala|url=http://search.informit.com.au/documentSummary;dn=137483878548865;res=IELAPA|journal=Historic Environment|volume=23|issue=2|pages=12}}</ref>\n** ''The Great Barrier Reef'' (IMAX), 1982; technical consultants<ref name=\":3\" />\n** ''Operation Shark Bite'', 1982<ref name=\":0\" />\n** ''Give Sharks a Chance'', 1991; with [[Richard Dennison]] for [[National Geographic Society]] and the [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]]<ref name=\":2\" />\n** ''Shark Shocker'' 1993 (with Richard Dennison) for [[Channel 4|Channel 4 UK]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oranafilms.com.au/shark-shocker/|title=Shark Shocker {{!}} Orana Films|website=www.oranafilms.com.au|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref>\n** ''Shadow over the Reef'', 1993<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.screenaustralia.gov.au/the-screen-guide/c/Ron-Taylor-Film-Productions/8423/,%20https://www.screenaustralia.gov.au/the-screen-guide/c/Ron-Taylor-Film-Productions/8423/|title=Ron Taylor Film Productions - The Screen Guide|website=Screen Australia|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref>\n** ''Mystique of the Pearl'', for [[Film Australia]], 1995<ref name=\":2\" />\n** ''Shark Pod'', 1996<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.screenaustralia.gov.au/the-screen-guide/t/shark-pod-1997/13291/|title=Shark POD (1997) - The Screen Guide - Screen Australia|website=www.screenaustralia.gov.au|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref>\n** ''Shadow of the Shark'', 1999; for [[Australian Geographic]]<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n=== Television ===\n\n* ''[[Skippy the Bush Kangaroo]]'', [[List of Skippy the Bush Kangaroo episodes#Season 1 (1968\u20131969)|Episode 3]] \u2013 ''Golden Reef'' (1968) \u2013 original story & [[List of Skippy the Bush Kangaroo episodes#Season 2 (1969)|Episode 57]] \u2013 ''The Shark Taggers''(1969) \u2013 underwater sequences<ref name=\":2\" />\n* ''Contrabandits'' (30 episode series), 1967\u201368; underwater sequences and diving instruction for cast<ref name=\":2\" />\n* ''[[Barrier Reef (TV series)|Barrier Reef]]'' (39-episode series), 1971\u20131972; direction of underwater photography, stunt work and minor acting roles<ref name=\":3\" />\n* ''Taylor's Inner Space'' (13-episode series), 1972\u20131973 with soundtrack composed by [[Sven Libaek]] and narration by [[William Shatner]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/filmosearch/?role=nm0508715|title=Most Popular Movies and TV Shows With Sven Libaek|website=IMDb|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref>\n* ''[[Those Amazing Animals]]'', 1980\u20131981; contributed to underwater segments<ref name=\":2\" />\n* ''[[Fortress (1986 film)|Fortress]]'', 1985; underwater sequences<ref name=\":2\" />\n* ''Blue Wilderness'' (6 episodes)[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1992_cageless_shark-diving_expedition], 1992; with Richard Dennison for National Geographic and the Australian Broadcasting Corporation<ref name=\":2\" />\n* ''[[Flipper (1995 TV series)|Flipper]]'', 1995 series; underwater still photography<ref>{{Citation|title=Flipper (1995 TV series)|date=2019-09-20|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Flipper_(1995_TV_series)&oldid=916791620|work=Wikipedia|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref>\n\n=== Films ===\n\n* ''[[Age of Consent (film)|Age of Consent]]'', 1968<ref name=\":2\" />\n* ''[[The Intruders (1969 film)|The Intruders]]'' (also known as ''Skippy and the Intruders''), 1969<ref>{{Citation|title=The Intruders|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0130795/|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref>\n* ''[[Blue Water White Death|Blue Water, White Death]]'', 1971<ref>{{Citation|title=Blue Water, White Death|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0146496/|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref>\n* ''[[Jaws (film)|Jaws]]'', 1975<ref name=\":2\" />\n* ''[[Orca (film)|Orca]]'', 1976; live shark sequences<ref name=\":2\" />\n* ''[[The Last Wave]]'', 1977; underwater sequences<ref>{{Citation|title=The Last Wave (1977) - IMDb|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0076299/fullcredits|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref>\n* ''[[Jaws 2]]'', 1978<ref name=\":2\" />\n* ''[[Gallipoli (1981 film)|Gallipoli]]'', 1981; underwater sequences<ref>{{Citation|title=Gallipoli|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0082432/|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref>\n* ''[[A Dangerous Summer]]'' , 1982: underwater sequences<ref>{{Citation|title=A Dangerous Summer|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0082233/|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref>\n* ''[[The Year of Living Dangerously (film)|Year of Living Dangerously]]'', 1982<ref>{{Citation|title=The Year of Living Dangerously|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0086617/|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref>\n* ''[[The Blue Lagoon (1980 film)|The Blue Lagoon]]'', 1980; underwater sequences<ref name=\":2\" />\n* ''The Silent One'', 1983<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sbs.com.au/movies/review/silent-one-review|title=The Silent One Review|website=SBS Movies|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref>\n* ''[[Sky Pirates]]'', 1984, underwater sequences<ref>{{Citation|title=Sky Pirates (1986) - IMDb|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0091964/fullcredits|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref>\n* ''[[Frog Dreaming]]'', 1986<ref>{{Citation|title=The Quest|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0091810/|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref>\n* ''[[The Rescue (1988 film)|The Rescue]]'', for Walt Disney, 1987\n* ''[[Return to the Blue Lagoon]]'', 1990, underwater sequences<ref name=\":2\" />\n* ''[[Honeymoon in Vegas]]'', 1991, underwater sequences<ref name=\":2\" />\n* ''[[Police Story 4: First Strike]]'', 1995; underwater sequences<ref name=\":2\" />\n* ''[[The Island of Dr. Moreau (1996 film)|The Island of Dr Moreau]]'', 1995, live shark sequences<ref>{{Citation|title=The Island of Dr. Moreau|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0116654/|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref>\n\n=== Books ===\n\n* ''The Undersea Artistry'', 2017, Illustrated<ref name=\":4\" />\n* ''An Adventurous Life'', 2019, Memoirs<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n== Awards and Achievements ==\n\n* 1981 \u2013 NOGI award for Arts, Academy of Underwater Arts & Sciences<ref name=\":11\" />\n* 1986 \u2013 [[Order of the Golden Ark]] presented by his Royal Highness, [[Prince Bernhard of the Netherlands]]<ref name=\":8\" />\n* 1993 \u2013 SSI Platinum Pro 5000 Diver<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.divessi.com/en-IC/inside-ssi/pro-recognition/|title=SSI PROFESSIONAL RECOGNITION|website=www.divessi.com|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref>\n* 1997: American Nature Photographer of the year award (sponsored by the American Press Club) for a picture of a [[whale shark]] swimming with her nephew in Ningaloo Marine Park<ref name=\":7\" />\n* 2000 \u2013 membership of the Women Divers Hall of Fame<ref name=\":9\"/>\n* 2001 \u2013 the Centenary Medal and the Australian Senior Achiever of the year<ref name=\":9\" />\n* 2010 \u2013 Member of the [[Order of Australia]] (AM)<ref name=\":10\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Australian photographers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Order of Australia]]\n[[Category:Australian filmmakers]]\n[[Category:1935 births]]\n", "name_user": "JovanW", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEarly life:Corrected typo.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Valerie_Taylor_(diver)"}
{"title_page": "Fluke Corporation", "text_new": "{{multiple issues|\n{{primary sources|date=July 2014}}\n{{advert|date=October 2010}}\n{{More footnotes|date=May 2016}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Fluke Corporation\n| logo = Flukelogo.png\n| logo_size = 134px\n| type = [[Subsidiary company|Subsidiary]]\n| traded_as = {{unbulleted list|{{NYSE|FTV}}|[[S&P 500|S&P 500 Component]]}}\n| foundation = 1948 in [[Everett, Washington]], U.S.\n| location = Everett, Washington\n| key_people = Marc Tremblay([[President (corporate title)|President]])\n| industry = Industrial Test Products\n| parent = [[Fortive]]\n| homepage = {{URL|http://www.fluke.com}}\n| founder = John Fluke, Sr.\n| num_employees = 2,525 ({{as of|2016|May|lc=y}})<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/snapshot.asp?privcapid=176527|title=Company Overview of Fluke Corporation|publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]]|accessdate=May 11, 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Fluke Corporation''', a subsidiary of [[Fortive]], is a manufacturer of industrial test, measurement and diagnostic equipment including [[electronic test equipment]]. It was started in 1948 by [[John Fluke]], who was a friend and roommate of [[David Packard]], future co-founder of [[Hewlett-Packard]], when both were employed at [[General Electric]].\n\n== History ==\n\nFluke Corporation was founded in Washington state by John Fluke on October 7, 1953 as the John Fluke Manufacturing Company, Inc., producing electrical metering equipment.\n\nIn 1987 Fluke entered a partnership with the [[Netherlands|Dutch]] electronics manufacturer [[Philips]]. Aside from access to their respective oversea markets, the partnership brought to the development of the [[scopemeter]], an instrument combining features of an [[oscilloscope]] and a [[multimeter]]. Fluke finally puchased the testing and measurements division of Philips in 1993 for $41.8 millions.<ref>{{cite book |title=International Directory of Company Histories, Vol. 15 |date=1996 |publisher=St. James Press |url=http://www.fundinguniverse.com/company-histories/fluke-corporation-history/}}</ref> Notably, the Philips PM series of measurement instruments was rebranded as Fluke.\n\nFluke was bought by the [[Danaher Corporation]] in 1998. Danaher spun off several subsidiaries, including Fluke, in 2016 to create Fortive.<ref>{{cite web|author1=Zacks Equity Research|title=Danaher Completes Fortive Spin-Off, Trading to Begin Today|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/danaher-completes-fortive-spin-off-125312990.html|website=Yahoo Finance|accessdate=5 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Subsidiaries ==\n=== Pomona Electronics ===\nPomona Electronics is a company specializing in electronic test equipment and accessories. It was founded in 1951 by Joseph J. and Carl W. Musarra, who were brothers.<ref name=\"1974-10-12\">{{cite news |date=1974-10-12 |title=Local electronics firm expands again |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/25721569/progress_bulletin/ |newspaper=[[Progress Bulletin]] |via=[[Newspapers.com]] |accessdate=2018-11-26 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181126053803/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/25721569/progress_bulletin/ |archivedate=2018-11-26 }}</ref><ref name=\"1974-11-21\">{{cite news |date=1974-11-21 |title=Valley company enlarges plant |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/25721509/progress_bulletin/ |newspaper=[[Progress Bulletin]] |via=[[Newspapers.com]] |accessdate=2018-11-26 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181126053519/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/25721509/progress_bulletin/ |archivedate=2018-11-26 }}</ref> Founded to test [[cable harness]]es for examining television [[cathode-ray tube]]s.<ref name=\"1961-01-29\">{{cite news |date=1961-01-29 |title=Specialization Credited for Steady Growth |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/25721296/the_los_angeles_times/ |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |via=[[Newspapers.com]] |accessdate=2018-11-26 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181126052545/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/25721296/the_los_angeles_times/ |archivedate=2018-11-26 }}</ref> the company started in a factory location around the size of a [[living room]].<ref name=\"1961-01-29\"/> By 1976, it was owned by [[ITT Industries]],<ref name=\"1976-01-24\">{{cite news |date=1976-01-24 |title=25-Year Honors |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/25721447/progress_bulletin/ |newspaper=[[Progress Bulletin]] |via=[[Newspapers.com]] |accessdate=2018-11-26 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181126053242/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/25721447/progress_bulletin/ |archivedate=2018-11-26 }}</ref> which in 1999 sold it to Fluke.<ref name=\"1999-01-25\">{{cite news |date=1999-01-25 |title=Fluke acquires Pomona Electronics. |url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-53878058.html |newspaper=Air Conditioning, Heating & Refrigeration News |via=[[HighBeam Research]] |accessdate=2018-11-26 |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20181126052108/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-53878058.html |archivedate=2018-11-26 }}</ref> In 2002, Pomona Electronics relocated its manufacturing facility to [[Everett, Washington]].<ref name=\"Smith2002-04-16\">{{cite news |last=Smith |first=Kevin |date=2002-04-16 |title=2 firms planning to leave Pomona - Companies will take 150 jobs with them |newspaper=[[Inland Valley Daily Bulletin]] }}</ref>\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery>\nImage:Fluke 115 multimeter.jpg|A Fluke 115 multimeter\nImage:Fluke 8010a.JPG|A Fluke 8010a bench multimeter\nImage:Fluke 45.jpg|A Fluke 45 Dual Display bench multimeter\nImage:Fluke 5500.jpg|A Fluke 5500 calibrator\nImage:Clampmeter Fluke 337.jpg|A Fluke 337 clamp multimeter\nImage:FLUKE networks IntelliTone Pro 200.JPG|The Fluke Networks IntelliTone Pro LAN probing kit\nImage:Banana plug adapter.JPG|Adapter between a female [[BNC connector]] and banana plugs manufactured by Pomona.\nImage:Binding post adapter.JPG|Adapter between five-way binding posts and a male [[BNC connector]] manufactured by Pomona.\n</gallery>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==